<item>
            <title>[SOLR-9915] PeerSync alreadyInSync check is not backwards compatible</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-9915</link>
                <project id="12310230" key="SOLR">Solr</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The fingerprint check added to PeerSync in &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-9446&quot; title=&quot;Leader failure after creating a freshly replicated index can send nodes into recovery even if index was not changed&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SOLR-9446&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SOLR-9446&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; works fine when all servers are running 6.3 but this means it&apos;s hard to do a rolling upgrade from e.g. 6.2.1 to 6.3 because the 6.3 server sends a request to a 6.2.1 server to get a fingerprint and then gets a NPE because the older server doesn&apos;t return the expected field in its response.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This leads to the PeerSync completely failing, and results in a full index replication from scratch, copying all index files over the network. We noticed this happening when we tried to do a rolling upgrade on one of our 6.2.1 clusters to 6.3. Unfortunately this amount of replication was hammering our disks and network, so we had to do a full shutdown, upgrade all to 6.3 and restart, which was not ideal for a production cluster.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The attached patch should behave more gracefully in this situation, as it will typically return false for alreadyInSync() and then carry on doing the normal re-sync based on versions.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
